title: siren_head
body:
Siren Head is a hostile cryptid and urban legend created by the artist Trevor Henderson. [b]Siren Head[/b] itself is a 40-foot-tall humanoid creature with a heavily emaciated, near-skeletal frame covered in dried, mummified flesh the color of rusty metal. It's limbs are disproportionately long and thin, with arms as long as it's legs, ending in huge, bony hands. Where it's head and neck would be is a thin pole of flesh with two sirens attached to them [i](hence the name)[/i], and several black wires snaking around it's "neck" and into it's upper shoulders, pressed against it's abdomen. These speakers are the only metal parts of it's body, fused to the neck by tendrils of skin and capable of swiveling around it much like the head of an owl. Some images depict [b]Siren Head's[/b] speakers with toothy, lipless human-like jaws and a long, retractable thin snake-like tongue. [quote]
Trevor Henderson said: though the teeth are only visible on a certain radio frequency.
[/quote]

title: ukagaka
body:
A Japanese computer program that provides mascot characters on the user's desktop. Also referred to as "偽ペルソナウェア with 偽春菜" (Fake personaware with Nise-Haruna), "あれ以外の何か with 任意" (Are Igai no Nanika with [[Nin'i-tan]]), "何か" (Nanika), and "偽春菜" (Nise-Haruna).

When the user launches the program (called Baseware), cute (or weird) characters called Ghosts (usually a set of two) appear on the screen, have random conversations, do things at specific times and perform actions in response to events, such as being touched by the mouse. Additional trivial functions are available, such as having them check incoming email, synchronizing the clock and making online updates.

Ghosts can be made by users, and at its height of popularity around the year [[2002]], a countless amount (in the thousands, according to one theory) of diverse Ghosts created by users were being distributed. Even simple graphic files of Ghost forms (called "Shells") were being circulated as freeware.

The most famous Ghosts are "[[sakura_(ukagaka)|Sakura]] & [[Unyuu]]," which are installed by default by Baseware, along with the famous "[[emily_(ukagaka)|Emily]] and Teddy" that were default Ghosts of SSP, a famous Ukagaka-compatible Baseware.

title: walk_on_water
body:
Walk on Water is a completed novel series written by Jang Mokdan and illustrated as a manhwa by Jaxx. Released in 2018, it has been published by Lezhin.

Starring in gay porn was never on Ed’s bucket list. He’s straight, he’s not an exhibitionist, and he has a decent career in security. That said, he also has a debt that he’s been working to pay off for years now, and he can barely keep up with the accruing interest. If having gay sex in front of a camera is the way to digging himself out of this pit, then he’s willing to be filmed for that money shot. But when he meets Glenn, the charismatic CEO of a gay porn production company, Ed finds himself falling into something much deeper than financial debt. Now, Ed is coming for the money…but will he be staying for Glenn?

title: sterling_smg
body:
A British 9×19mm Parabellum [[submachine gun]]. It was tested with the British Army in 1944–1945 as a replacement for the [[Sten gun]], but it did not start to replace it until 1953. A successful and reliable design, it remained as standard issue with the British Army until 1994, when it began to be replaced by the [[L85]] [[assault rifle]].

The Sterling utilizes conventional blowback open bolt design. Its bolt has helical grooves cut into the surface to remove dirt and fouling from the inside of the receiver to increase reliability. The weapon is constructed entirely of (stamped) steel and plastic and has a bottom-folding stock. Similar to the its predecessor, the [[magazine (weapon)|magazine]] is inserted sideways.

title: oushitsu_kyoushi_heine
body:
[b]Oushitsu Kyoushi Heine[/b], also known by its English name [b]The Royal Tutor[/b], is a comedy, historical-inspired manga series by [[Akai Higasa]]. It has an anime adaptation and stage play, as well as an original movie.

The protagonist [[Heine Wittgenstein]], a man often mistaken for a small child, has been summoned to the royal palace of Granzreich by [[viktor von granzreich|the king]] to act as the royal tutor to the four younger princes—[[kai von granzreich|Kai]], [[bruno von granzreich|Bruno]], [[leonhard von granzreich|Leonhard]], and [[licht von granzreich|Licht]]–turning them into capable candidates to the throne. However, he finds his task difficult because of the complicated personalities of his charges, who had managed to cause every tutor they had to quit. The story follows Heine’s journey to offer the princes the education they need most, help them with their issues, and unravel the complicated nature of both the royalty’s life and his own mysterious past.

body:
RPK is Upotte's personification of the RPK light support weapon. She's tall, busty, athletic, extremely competitive, and a staunch supporter of Red Steel High's ideology.

She normally wears the same standard Sailor Suit uniform as her classmates, but stands out due to her distinctive red lipstick. She's also been depicted wearing a maid outfit, overalls and talk top, and she uses a Fox mask when she wishes to hide her identity.

In the Upotte and /ak/ communities, she is often depicted as a futanari and many running jokes about her "extra parts" exist. Hence the "RPK has benis" meme. In [[Metal Gear 2]] and [[Metal Gear Solid]], he wears a [[tank top]], [[black gloves]], a [[ponytail]], and either a [[whistle around neck|whistle around his neck]] or [[dog tags]]. He's also commonly featured with a [[prosthetic arm]], but it's unknown if he actually got a prosthetic in canon.

In [[Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain]], he becomes a [[double amputee]] after being tortured. He wears a [[beret]], a [[green shirt|green]] [[collared shirt]], a [[red_necktie]], a [[coat]], a [[cane]], a [[vest]], and a [[stubble]].

title: metal_gear_solid_3:_snake_eater
body:
[b]Metal Gear Solid 3: Snake Eater[/b] (メタルギアソリッド3 スネーク・イーター, Metaru Gia Soriddo Surī Sunēku Ītā?, commonly abbreviated to MGS3) is an award-winning stealth action video game directed by [[Kojima Hideo]]. Snake Eater was developed by Konami Computer Entertainment Japan and published by [[Konami]] for the [[PlayStation 2]], and was released on November 17, 2004 in North America; December 16, 2004 in Japan; March 4, 2005 in Europe; and on March 17, 2005 in Australia. 

The game, which serves as a prequel to the entire [[Metal Gear (series)|]] series, was followed by two direct sequels titled [[Metal Gear Solid: Portable Ops]] and [[Metal Gear Solid: Peace Walker]].

Set in the Cold War era [[Soviet]] Union, the story centers on FOX operative Naked Snake as he attempts to rescue a weapons designer and sabotage an experimental superweapon. While previous games were set in a primarily urban environment, Snake Eater adopts a 60s Soviet jungle setting, with the high tech, near-future trappings of previous Metal Gear Solid games being replaced with the wilderness. While the setting has changed, the game's focus remains on stealth and infiltration, while retaining the series' self-referential, fourth wall-breaking sense of humor. The story of Snake Eater is told through numerous cut scenes and radio conversations.

title: kojima_hideo
body:
Born August 24, 1963 in Tokyo, Japan. A famous Japanese [[video game]] director originally employed at [[Konami]]. He is the director of his own company, Kojima Productions, and was promoted to Vice President of Konami Digital Entertainment in early 2011. His previous positions include being vice president of Konami Computer Entertainment Japan.

He is the creator and director of a number of successful video games, including the [[metal_gear_(series)|Metal Gear]] series of stealth games and the adventure games [[Snatcher]] and [[Policenauts]], and he also produced series such as [[Zone of the Enders]] and [[Bokura no Taiyou]]. 

Kojima is consistently named by fans and experts alike as being one of the most influential and innovative directors and writers in the video game industry, although he is not without detractors; notably, Agness Kaku, translator of [i][[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons Of Liberty]][/i] has stated in a 2011 Skype interview that Kojima is "very bad at character" and "extremely conventional, as in non-creative, when it comes to plotting."

title: mortar_shell
body:
[b][[Explosive]] [[ammunition]][/b] that is loaded in and fired from [b][[mortar (weapon)|mortar]]s[/b]. It is also commonly referred as mortar round or [[bomb]]. It comes in various calibers. Mortar shells generally comes in two main varieties: fin-stabilized and spin-stabilized.
Lighter (approximately 60 mm) mortar shells could be thrown by hand like [[grenade]]s, but with shorter range due to its weight and higher risk. [spoiler]In fact, few "soldiers during World War II could do that":[https://www.wearethemighty.com/popular/yes-world-war-ii-soldiers-could-throw-mortar-rounds-like-grenades/]. This action is featured on movies like Saving Private Ryan and Hacksaw Ridge.[/spoiler]

Mortars can fire different types of shells. Some of these are:
* [b]High explosive.[/b] This is a normal round which explodes when it hits the ground.
* [b]Smoke round.[/b] This creates thick smoke, it can be various colours. It is fired on enemy positions or in open areas to block visibility, so friendly forces can move without being visible.
* [b]White phosphorus.[/b] This makes a thick [[smoke]] screen to blind and burn the enemy, causing second and third degree burns from the explosion.
* [b][[Illumination]] round.[/b] This is a flare which hangs underneath a parachute. It lights up the [[battlefield]] at night.

"Wikipedia page":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mortar_(weapon)#Ammunition]

title: rickshaw
body:
A two-wheeled vehicle intended to be pulled by a person. The English word is a borrowing from the Japanese [i]jinrikisha[/i], literally "human-powered cart".

Formerly ubiquitous in many Asian cities, the introduction of automobiles and trains caused their gradual disappearance over the course of the 20th century. They retain vintage appeal for many however, and can still be found in some areas of Kyoto and Tokyo.

title: texas_cloverleaf
body:
A spine-targeting [[submission hold]] where the wrestler performing the move stands at the feet of the supine opponent, grabs the opponent's legs, and lifts them up. The wrestler then bends one leg so that the shin is behind the knee of the straight leg and places the ankle of the straight leg in their armpit. With the same arm, they reach around the ankle and through the opening formed by the legs, and lock their hands together. The wrestler then steps over his opponent, turning the opponent over as in a [[scorpion deathlock]] or a [[boston crab]] and proceeds to squat and lean back.

It is also known as just the [i]Cloverleaf[/i], or [i]Texas Cloverhold[/i] in Japan. Famous users include wrestling legend [[Dory Funk Jr]] (who is the innovator of the hold), WCW & [[WWE]] alumnus Dean Malenko, [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] wrestler [[Tanahashi Hiroshi]], WWE wrestler [[Sheamus]], and [[Tokyo Joshi Pro Wrestling]] wrestler [[Itou Maki (wrestler)|]]. The late wrestling legend [[Eddie Guerrero]] has a variation of the Texas Cloverleaf where he performs the maneuver from a standing position, which enabled him to pull the opponent's legs up high enough to where he could add pressure to the hold by sticking one of his knees into the other wrestler's back. Guerrero referred to the move as the [i]Lasso from El Paso[/i], making reference to his hometown of El Paso, Texas.

body:
Georgy Maximilianovich Malenkov, a politician of the Soviet Union, was for the short period of time that he was interim leader between Stalin and Khruschev, the most powerful person in the Soviet Union.

After losing power he became the head of a hydroelectric power plant in Ust-Kamenogorsk, Ekibastuz GRES-1 thermal power station, but his name was eventually struck from the communist party register.

In Japan, he was known for his weak presence and was often called ”マなんとかさん (Ma-whatshisname-san)” and people joked that ”the reason the Soviet Union fell was because he had disrupted the 'Bald-Hairy Theory’.”

title: gakusei_undou
body:
A Japanese term for student activism that is often used to refer to "the Japanese New Left wave":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_New_Left from the 1950s to 70s, its political movements and groups.

Various individual groups, political movements and incidents are associated with this term. For example the "Kakumaru-ha":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japan_Revolutionary_Communist_League_%28Revolutionary_Marxist_Faction%29], the "Chuukaku-ha":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revolutionary_Communist_League,_National_Committee], the post-50s "Zengakuren":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zengakuren], "Zenkyoutou":[https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%85%A8%E5%AD%A6%E5%85%B1%E9%97%98%E4%BC%9A%E8%AD%B0], "Toudai Funsou":[https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%9D%B1%E5%A4%A7%E7%B4%9B%E4%BA%89], etc. When one of those organizations, "the Rengou Sekigun":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Red_Army], caused the "Asama-Sansou incident":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asama-Sans%C5%8D_incident], and members of "the Nihon Sekigun":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_Red_Army] were found to be involved in the "Lod Airport massacre":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lod_Airport_massacre], they lost all support from the public and went into decline, even impacting broader political discussion by rendering it a "private":https://twitter.com/OnTakahashi/status/1341536212280954880 matter.

They are stereotyped as being equipped with construction [[helmet]]s, dust [[mask]]s and [[log|square timber]] (sometimes [[lead pipe|steel pipes]] and [[Molotov cocktail]]s), sticking [[flyer]]s with various [[propaganda]] slogans (for example, "Never allow!!" "Crush the unfair **!!" "We will win this conflict!!" etc.) all over the place, and for separating into numerous groups and infighting. The various portmanteaus using Geba and Aji were created from student activism, and each derive from "gewalt" (German for "violence") and "agitation".

The square timber mentioned earlier are called "geba-bou":[http://dic.pixiv.net/a/%E3%82%B2%E3%83%90%E6%A3%92] (gewalt stick), internal conflict is called "uchi-geba":https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%86%85%E3%82%B2%E3%83%90 (internal gewalt), flyers are "aji-bira":https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E3%82%A2%E3%82%B8%E3%83%93%E3%83%A9 (agitation flyers), and the fonts used for these purposes are called "geba-moji":http://www.pixiv.net/search.php?s_mode=s_tag_full&word=%E3%82%B2%E3%83%90%E6%96%87%E5%AD%97 (gewalt fonts).

title: lotus
body:
An aquatic plant belonging to the Nelumbonaceae family of flowering plants. The lotus has prominent blooms (of pink or white hues) rising 8-12 inches above the water, each with a flattened central seed pod structure and fully circular leaves with centrally-attached stems. These features help distinguish it from the [[water lily flower]] (Nymphaea), with which it is often confused.

[i]Nelumbo nucifera[/i] (also known as the Sacred or Indian Lotus) will probably be the plant of interest to Danbooru image taggers, being a divine symbol in Hinduism and Buddhism. It conveys the virtues of purity and non-attachment; it is associated with beauty, elegance, and grace.

When she begins to think about going out of the mountains and moving to the city, her guardian Sagara Yukimasa recommends her to enter a high school in Tokyo and forces his son [[sagara_miyuki|Miyuki]] to serve [[suzuhara_izumiko|Izumiko]] for life. [[sagara_miyuki|Miyuki]] and [[suzuhara_izumiko|Izumiko]] repel each other but their relationship begins to change when a terrifying accident occurs on the school excursion. Living by the sea, protecting the sea, and journeying across the sea... They're the Blue Mermaids!

Because of a shift in tectonic plates around 100 years ago, Japan lost much of its area to submergence. To preserve Japan's territories, coastal cities sprung up, one after the other. Eventually, they became marine cities, and along with the expansion of sea-lanes to connect them, the need arose for a sizable staff to protect the seas.

At the same time, maritime jobs were becoming more popular among women. Hence, the Blue Mermaids, tasked with keeping the seas safe, had become every female student's dream job. title: bald_eagle
body:
The Bald Eagle ([i]Haliaeetus leucocephalus[/i]) is an [[eagle]] found in North America.  As an adult they feature dark brown feathers with white head and tail feathers.  Their beaks, feet, and irises are bright yellow.  The bald eagle has a body length of 70–102 cm (28–40 in) and typical wingspan between 1.8 and 2.3 m (5 ft 11 in and 7 ft 7 in).  Their mass is normally between 3 and 6.3 kg (6.6 and 13.9 lb). Males' average 4.1 kg (9.0 lb) and females average 5.6 kg (12 lb). 

The word "bald" in their name is derived from an older meaning referring to the white of their head and tail. Their species name is Latinized Ancient Greek for "white" and "head".

The Bald Eagle has cultural importance to the [[United States]] and [[Native American]]s. It is the national [[bird]] and symbol of the United States of America. It is featured on the Great Seal of the United States that was adopted by the Continental Congress in 1782.  For various [[Native American]] tribes it holds spiritual and religious significance, and its feathers are central to many of their religious and spiritual customs.

[b]Lars Ulrich[/b] (/ˈʌlrɪk/ UL-rik; Danish: [lɑːs ˈulˀʁæg̊]; born December 26, 1963) is a Danish drummer and one of the founding members of the American heavy metal band [[Metallica]]. 

He was born in Gentofte, Denmark to an upper-middle-class family. A tennis player in his youth (he is the son of former tennis pro Torben Ulrich), Ulrich moved to Los Angeles, California at age sixteen in the summer of 1980 to pursue his training; though rather than playing tennis, he began playing the drums. 

After publishing an advertisement in a local Los Angeles newspaper called "The Recycler", Ulrich met [[James Hetfield]] and formed Metallica in 1981.

title: alan_shepard
body:
[b]Alan Bartlett Shepard, Jr.[/b] (November 18, 1923 – July 21, 1998) was an American naval aviator, test pilot, flag officer, and NASA astronaut who in May 5, 1961 became the second person, and the first American, in space. 

His [[Mercury (spacecraft)|Mercury spacecraft]] flight was designed to enter space, but not to achieve orbit. Ten years later Shepard commanded the Apollo 14 mission, piloting the lander to the most accurate landing of the Apollo missions. He became the fifth person to walk on the Moon, and the only Mercury astronaut to walk on the moon. During the mission he hit two golf balls on the lunar surface.

He retired from the US Navy and NASA in 1974. During retirement Shepard became a successful businessman. 

Alan Shepard died of leukemia in 1998, five weeks before the death of his wife of 53 years. They were survived by their three daughters.

title: colecovision
body:
The [b]ColecoVision[/b] was Coleco Industries' second-generation American home [[game console]] that was released in August 1982. 

The ColecoVision offered a closer experience to more powerful [[arcade]] game systems compared to competitors such as the Atari 2600, along with the means to expand the system's basic hardware.

The initial catalog of twelve games included [[Nintendo]]'s [[Donkey Kong]] as the pack-in cartridge, [[Sega]]'s graphically impressive [[Zaxxon]], and some lesser known arcade titles that found a larger audience on the console, such as [[Lady Bug]], [[Cosmic Avenger]], and [[Venture]]. Approximately 145 titles in total were published as ROM [[game cartridge]]s for the system between 1982 and 1984.

Coleco withdrew from the [[video game]] market in 1985, thus ColecoVision was discontinued the same year.

[b][i]Battlestar Galactica[/i][/b] is an American [[science_fiction|Sci-fi]] media franchise created by Glen A. Larson that began with the original television series in 1978 and was later followed by a short-run sequel series ([i]Galactica 1980[/i]), a line of book adaptations, original novels, comic books, a board game, and video games. 

The re-imagined version of Battlestar Galactica aired as a two-part, three-hour miniseries developed by Ronald D. Moore and David Eick in 2003. That miniseries led to a very popular weekly television series, which later aired from 2004 to 2009. A prequel series, [i]Caprica[/i], aired in 2010.

All Battlestar Galactica productions share the premise that in a distant part of the universe, a humanoid civilization is engaged in a lengthy war with a cybernetic race known as the [[Cylon]]s, whose goal is the extermination of the human race. The remainder of humanity is forced to flee their homes and search for the fabled "13th Colony"- also known as Earth.

body:
[b]Clifford Lee "Cliff" Burton[/b] (February 10, 1962 – September 27, 1986) was an American musician, best known as the bass guitarist for the American thrash [[heavy metal]] band [[Metallica]].

Burton joined Metallica in 1982 and performed on the band's first three studio albums, [i]Kill 'Em All[/i], [i][[Ride the Lightning]][/i], and [i][[Master of Puppets]][/i]. He also received a posthumous writing credit for the song "To Live Is to Die" from the band's fourth studio album [i][[...And Justice For All]][/i].

On September 27, 1986, Burton died in a bus accident in rural southern Sweden as the band was touring in support of the Master of Puppets album. In 2011, an online Rolling Stone reader poll selected him as the ninth greatest bassist of all time.

body:
[b]Atari[/b] is a corporate and brand name owned by several entities since its inception in 1972, currently by Atari Interactive, a subsidiary of the French publisher Atari, SA (ASA).

The original Atari, Inc., an American company founded in Sunnyvale, California in 1972 by Nolan Bushnell and Ted Dabney, was a pioneer in [[arcade]] [[video game]]s, [[game console]]s, and home computers. 

The company's products, such as the innovative [[Pong]] and the very popular [[Atari 2600]] console, helped define the electronic entertainment industry from the 70s to the mid 80s.

In 1984, the original Atari Inc. was split due to its role in the "video game crash of 1983":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game_crash_of_1983, it was refounded as [i]Atari Corporation[/i] in 1985 before dissolved in 1998, its brand were later sold off to French company Infogrames, who rebranded themselves as [i]Atari, SA[/i] and remains active to this day.

title: united_states_postal_service
body:
The United States Postal Service (USPS) is an independent agency of the executive branch of the [[United states|United States]] federal government responsible for providing postal service in the United States. It is one of the few government agencies explicitly authorized by the United States Constitution.

The USPS has a monopoly on "letter" delivery within the United States and operates under a universal service obligation, both of which are defined across a broad set of legal mandates, which obligate it to provide uniform price and quality across the entirety of its service area. USPS has exclusive access to letter boxes marked "U.S. Mail" and personal letterboxes in the United States, but has to compete against private package delivery services, such as [[United Parcel Service]], [[FedEx]], and [[Amazon_(company)|]].

title: terastallization
body:
A battle mechanic introduced in [[Pokemon SV]].

[quote]This phenomenon is found only in the Paldea region and makes Pokémon shine and glimmer like gems.
When a Pokémon Terastallizes, a Tera Jewel appears above the Pokémon’s head like a crown, and the Pokémon’s body glistens like a cut gemstone.
 
All Pokémon in Paldea can Terastallize to gain special powers, and Terastallization allows players to enhance their battle strategies by increasing the power of any moves that have the same type as their Pokémon’s Tera Type. There are 18 types, meaning there are countless combinations of Pokémon and Tera Types.
 
Players can Terastallize a Pokémon once per battle and the transformation will last until the battle ends. Players will need a [[Tera Orb]] to Terastallize a Pokémon, which will need to be recharged after each use. Players can charge their Tera Orb by touching crystals overflowing with Terastal energy or by going to a Pokémon Center.[/quote]

title: cossack_dance
body:
Hopak (correct name, Ukrainian: гопа́к, IPA: [ɦoˈpɑk]), also known as "[[squatting|Squat]] dance", is a [[ukraine|Ukrainian]] [[folk dance]] originating as a male dance among the [[cossack|Zaporozhian Cossacks]], but later danced by couples, male soloists, and mixed groups of dancers. It is performed most often as a solitary concert dance by amateur and professional Ukrainian dance ensembles, as well as other performers of folk dances. It has also been incorporated into larger artistic opuses such as operas, ballets and theatre.

The hopak is often popularly referred to as the "National Dance of Ukraine" and has become very popular in Slavic countries, in particular [[Poland]], Belarus and Russia. There are similar folkloric dance tunes known as Sirmpa in Leros, [[Greece]].

title: shanghai_doll
body:
[[Touhou]] character. The physical component for [[Alice Margatroid]]'s spellcard "Eerily Luminous Shanghai Doll" in [[Perfect Cherry Blossom]] / [[Immaterial and Missing Power]], as well as her familiar in [[Imperishable Night]].

Shanghai is a very popular supporting character (or artifact) in [[Touhou]] fan art depicting Alice.

Some comic artists give the [[doll]] a personality and feelings of its own, making it a "master doll" that helps control the lesser dolls. Others show it as Alice's primary magically-controlled "puppet". These points of view can be mixed, possibly to give an impression of Alice "debating with herself" through doll use, reminiscent of the way ventriloquists use puppets. Sometimes she/it is even depicted as lacking "doll" traits entirely, resembling a [[minigirl]].

Another view is that Shanghai is a type or class of magical dolls rather than an individual doll. This is based on the fact that several Shanghai dolls are seen simultaneously in [[Perfect Cherry Blossom]].

Canonically, Shanghai, like all the rest of Alice's dolls, is a mindless drone that requires direct supervision for all but the most basic of autonomous action, despite Alice's ongoing efforts to create a truly sapient construct. When a fanwork depicts Alice finally succeeding, Shanghai is usually the subject.

title: jiang_zemin
body:
Former General Secretary of the [[China|Chinese]] [[Communism|Communist Party]] (1989—2002) and Paramount leader (1989—2004).

Has become a recurring [[meme]] within the Chinese internet community, mainly due to his eccentric behavior and his role on the Chinese media censorship (particularly his role duing the [[Tiananmen Square]] protests).

He is usually being referred to as "Elder Jiang" and is depicted as a sort of "The Big Brother" character who watches over the internet and supposedly punish anyone who is "crossing the line". Though he is later remembered fondly for the relatively loosened control over the people, especially during the era of [[Xi Jinping]].

Jiang Zemin passed away on November 30, 2022 after complications from leukemia.

title: oscar_gonzalez_loyo_(person)
body:
[b]Oscar González Loyo[/b] (11 April 1959 in Mexico City - 7 February 2021) was a comic book artist, author of [[Karmatron y Los Transformables]].

Oscar González Loyo did his first semi-professional comic art page in 1973, in the Mexican comic Las Aventuras de Capulina, when he was only 14 years old. He cited [[Walt Disney]], [[Tezuka Osamu]] and "Will Eisner":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Will_Eisner as important influences in his art style.

Over the years he worked on titles like Las Aventuras de Cepillín, Las Aventuras de Parchís, Katy la Oruga, El Monje Loco, [[The Flintstones]], Karmatrón y Los Transformables, [[mach_go_go_go|The New Speed Racer]] color book, Tiny Toons, Looney Tunes, [[The Simpsons]] Comics and [[Bart Simpson]] Comics.

González Loyo also worked on the covers of the [[tetsuwan_atom|Astroboy]], [[jungle_taitei|Kimba]] and [[Tetsujin_28-gou|Gigantor]]'s American VHS and Laser Disc editions in the late eighties and early nineties. In 2000, he earned the Eisner Award at Comic-Con International for his work on [[Bart Simpson's Treehouse of Horror]], along with Jill Thompson, Steve Steere Jr., Scott Shaw, Sergio Aragonés, and Doug TenNapel.

title: zacek
body:
The main protagonist of the [[Karmatron y los Transformables]] science fiction and [[fantasy]] Mexican comic series from the 80s.

[b]Zacek[/b] ("White Star" in the [[Maya (culture)|Maya]] language) is a valiant and intrepid young humanoid [[alien]] prince from planet [[Zuyua]] who is also an expert at cybernetics. He is the creator of the [i]Transformables[/i] (also known as the [i]Stellar Warriors[/i]), a group of brave and powerful sentient Transformers who protect the Zuyua people. 

He is very skilled at combat and has white hair.

[spoiler]Zacek can transform into [[Karmatron]] with the powers of his kalpe-om belt by reciting a sacred mantra.
